## USER RESEARCH

### Audience Intent on This Page
The reader landing on this post is in **active purchase mode**. She already knows she wants almond-shaped press-ons — she's not discovering the shape here. Her real questions are: *Which ones won't fall off? Which ones look real and not plasticky? Do they suit my lifestyle (active, working, mum)? Is the price justified?* She wants editorial permission to buy a specific set, not a wall of options.

**Secondary intent layer:** a meaningful portion are first-time press-on buyers who want reassurance that they can make this work at home. They carry anxiety about sizing, application, and nail damage — and will convert faster if the post dissolves those fears directly.

### Top 5 Pain Points (sourced from Quora, FASHION Magazine reviews, NBCNews/Select, ShadePax research data, mindbodygreen, brand review sections, beauty editor accounts)

1. **Lifting and early popping off** — The number one frustration. Users report one or two nails popping off within days, especially after washing hair or dishes. Root cause is almost always inadequate nail prep (skipping alcohol degreasing step) or wrong sizing. Competitors rarely explain *why* this happens — they just list tips.

2. **"They look obviously fake"** — Sizing that is too wide causes nail-to-skin overlap at sidewalls; too-thick application makes nails look bulky and artificial. Real user language: "You can just tell they're fake from a mile away." ShadePax 2025 consumer research confirms this is the top reported frustration at ~70% of first-time users.

3. **Not knowing which size to pick** — Sizing anxiety is real and universal. Users describe guessing, ordering wrong, and having packs with no usable sizes for their specific nails. Wide or flat nail beds compound this. The 15-size kits (vs 12-size drugstore kits) matter and need to be called out.

4. **Damage anxiety / "are these bad for my nails?"** — Dr Hannah Kopelman (dermatologist, DermOnDemand, NBCNews Sept 2025) confirms: press-ons are not inherently damaging, but back-to-back wear with no breaks causes brittleness and cuticle issues. Glue adhesive can trigger sensitivity in some people. The audience wants a dermatologist-backed honest answer, not brand PR spin.

5. **Confusion between glue vs tabs — and when to use which** — Users don't know when to use nail glue vs adhesive tabs. Tabs feel "safer" but fall off faster. Glue lasts longer but feels intimidating. Users get the wrong longevity from the wrong method and blame the product. Real user phrasing: "tabs keep falling off after one day" — actually a prep issue (no alcohol wipe), not a product issue.

### User Sentiment
Excited but cautious — the audience is enthusiastic about the concept of at-home press-ons but carries genuine anxiety about execution and results, shaped by one or two bad experiences with cheap kits or poor application.

